<p:sld xmlns:a="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/drawingml/2006/main" xmlns:r="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/officeDocument/2006/relationships" xmlns:p="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/presentationml/2006/main"><p:cSld><p:spTree><p:nvGrpSpPr><p:cNvPr id="1" name=""/><p:cNvGrpSpPr/><p:nvPr/></p:nvGrpSpPr><p:grpSpPr><a:xfrm><a:off x="0" y="0"/><a:ext cx="0" cy="0"/><a:chOff x="0" y="0"/><a:chExt cx="0" cy="0"/></a:xfrm></p:grpSpPr><p:sp><p:nvSpPr><p:cNvPr id="2" name="Title 1"><a:extLst><a:ext uri="{FF2B5EF4-FFF2-40B4-BE49-F238E27FC236}"><a16:creationId xmlns:a16="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/drawing/2014/main" id="{0B229C1A-A81A-7FFA-04A7-E53B1EDAD7D3}"/></a:ext></a:extLst></p:cNvPr><p:cNvSpPr><a:spLocks noGrp="1"/></p:cNvSpPr><p:nvPr><p:ph type="title"/></p:nvPr></p:nvSpPr><p:spPr/><p:txBody><a:bodyPr/><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/><a:t>Presentations to senior management can be quite tricky, so here are a few more tips (1/2)</a:t></a:r></a:p></p:txBody></p:sp><p:sp><p:nvSpPr><p:cNvPr id="3" name="Content Placeholder 2"><a:extLst><a:ext uri="{FF2B5EF4-FFF2-40B4-BE49-F238E27FC236}"><a16:creationId xmlns:a16="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/drawing/2014/main" id="{C70489A3-2583-6D9B-F661-D295DBFA4DAD}"/></a:ext></a:extLst></p:cNvPr><p:cNvSpPr><a:spLocks noGrp="1"/></p:cNvSpPr><p:nvPr><p:ph idx="1"/></p:nvPr></p:nvSpPr><p:spPr/><p:txBody><a:bodyPr/><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" b="1" dirty="0"/><a:t>Start with the conclusion or recommendation</a:t></a:r><a:br><a:rPr lang="en-US" b="1" dirty="0"/></a:br><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" sz="2000" i="1" dirty="0"/><a:t>Senior management are busy people, and they may not always bother reading through the entire deck to get to your main point. Put an executive summary upfront so they can get to the results and recommendations first before going through the other details.</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" b="1" dirty="0"/><a:t>Tie the topic to business value</a:t></a:r><a:br><a:rPr lang="en-US" b="1" dirty="0"/></a:br><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" sz="2000" i="1" dirty="0"/><a:t>While it may be obvious to you why your work is important, this is unlikely so for senior management who have many things to take care of and are far removed from your work. Make sure you directly explain why they should care about your work.</a:t></a:r><a:endParaRPr lang="en-US" b="1" i="1" dirty="0"/></a:p><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" b="1" dirty="0"/><a:t>Explain what’s next and when it’ll be done</a:t></a:r><a:br><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/></a:br><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" sz="2000" i="1" dirty="0"/><a:t>An important part of management is the roadmap – they are not just concerned about what has been done, but what is coming up next. Explain what the next steps for your project are (eg deployment, further experimentation) and a rough timeline for its execution.</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:endParaRPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/></a:p></p:txBody></p:sp><p:sp><p:nvSpPr><p:cNvPr id="4" name="TextBox 3"><a:extLst><a:ext uri="{FF2B5EF4-FFF2-40B4-BE49-F238E27FC236}"><a16:creationId xmlns:a16="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/drawing/2014/main" id="{ECA523EF-744A-F594-DD34-DF28FD74D822}"/></a:ext></a:extLst></p:cNvPr><p:cNvSpPr txBox="1"/><p:nvPr/></p:nvSpPr><p:spPr><a:xfrm><a:off x="5992836" y="6262042"/><a:ext cx="5219115" cy="461665"/></a:xfrm><a:prstGeom prst="rect"><a:avLst/></a:prstGeom><a:noFill/></p:spPr><p:txBody><a:bodyPr wrap="square" rtlCol="0"><a:spAutoFit/></a:bodyPr><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:pPr algn="r"/><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" sz="1200" i="1" dirty="0"><a:latin typeface="Helvetica" pitchFamily="2" charset="0"/></a:rPr><a:t>Many of these are learnt from experience and also taken from “An Elegant Puzzle: Systems of Engineering Management” by Will Larson</a:t></a:r></a:p></p:txBody></p:sp></p:spTree><p:extLst><p:ext uri="{BB962C8B-B14F-4D97-AF65-F5344CB8AC3E}"><p14:creationId xmlns:p14="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/powerpoint/2010/main" val="1441876237"/></p:ext></p:extLst></p:cSld><p:clrMapOvr><a:masterClrMapping/></p:clrMapOvr></p:sld>